@Steve, we need sedan and hatchbacks manufactured in the US. We need core industry in this country. Foreign car manufacturers could develop and sell their entire product lines here in the US. A number already do this with a lot of their cars. This also reduces fossil fuel usage as the cars aren't shipped in giant container ships from foreign countries. American workers also benefit when they're not competing with countries with significantly lower wages, such as Mexico.

In addition, we can't build our own military if we don't have the manufacturing sector to produce the parts ourselves. Core industry has been outsourced courtesy of Wall Street investors more interested in profits than national security. Tariffs will incentivize corporations to build here in order to sell here. This also creates higher paying blue collar jobs, giving our workers more money to spend. Providing income tax breaks for buying American made products could potentially be used to offset the cost of tariffs on foreign goods. Such could be implemented by simply saving some sort of a receipt for "Made in America" purchases, maybe as simple as adding "MIA" next to line items on a receipt.

And, by the way, Intel and Micron are both electronic companies with lot of factories in the US that produce microchips, motherboards, etc. Buy their products and you'll re-enforce this industry.

